Webster Kindergarten Center, Lemmer Elementary, and Escanaba Upper Elementary are excitedly making plans for the fall. Class lists will be posted on the front windows of the respective buildings by 3:00 PM on August 25th and virtual Open House links (including building tours and teacher introductions) will be posted on the District's website and Facebook page on August 26th.

In an effort to keep the message clear and concise, comments or questions submitted via Facebook may be removed periodically.

Escanaba Jr/Sr High staff are planning a Virtual Open House that will be available on the 26th of August for students to 'tour' the school and view a slideshow of teachers. The in-person student orientations planned for August 10th and 11th have been cancelled.

Students will be able to look around the school and find their classes when they pick up their schedules:

8th grade - Aug. 13th
7th grade - Aug. 18th
6th grade - Aug. 19th
Hours: 7:00 - 11:00 AM and 11:30 AM - 2:30 PM

12th Grade: Wed., Aug. 12th (7-4pm) These are individual planning meetings, therefore different time frame.
11th Grade: Thurs. Aug. 13th (7- 11:00 and 11:30 - 2:30pm)
10th Grade: Tues., Aug. 18th (7 -11:00 and 11:30 - 2:30pm)
9th grade: Wed. Aug. 19th (7 - 11:00 and 11:30 - 2:30pm)

School Pictures will be taken at the time of schedule pick up so be sure to dress accordingly. Masks will be required for entry into the school.

Please contact the Jr/Sr High office for additional info.

post_text:
NOTICE OF PESTICIDE APPLICATION
Escanaba Area Public Schools

A pesticide application for the management of turf pests for weeds and fertilization will be made on Friday, July 24th, 2020 at the Athletic Field, specifically the football game fields located at Lake Shore Drive and 18th Avenue South, Escanaba, Michigan.

Lawn markers will be posted at the football fields following the application and re-entry is restricted until the lawn markers have been removed.

The product to be applied for the weed application is Momentum 4-Score (Triclopyr/Fluroxpyp, Sulfentrazone) for broadleaf weed control. The applicator is Nault’s Green Lawn Liquid Fertilizer, Inc.

For additional information, please contact the Director of Operations at (906) 786-4661 or acseter@eskymos.com. The National Pesticide Information Center phone number is 1-800 858-7378. The Michigan Department of Agriculture phone number is 1-800-292-3939.

post_text: Escanaba High School graduates Cassidy Magnuson, Emma Zuidema, Madison Quinn, and Gladstone graduate Olivia Capodilupo wanted to contribute to the fight for human rights and equality in our small community. They used tips collected while working at Jo to Go to purchase copies of Just Mercy by Bryan Stevenson for Mrs. Bishop's AP Language course. The non-fiction text exposes the flaws in the justice system while also offering hope for redemption and change. The generosity of the students demonstrates how the lessons taught in high school continue to positively change the world outside of the classroom.

NOTICE OF PESTICIDE APPLICATION
Escanaba Area Public Schools

A pesticide application for the management of turf pests for weeds and fertilization will be made on Friday, June 12th, 2020 at the Athletic Field, specifically the football game fields located at Lake Shore Drive and 18th Avenue South, Escanaba, Michigan.

Lawn markers will be posted at the football fields following the application and re-entry is restricted until the lawn markers have been removed.

The product to be applied for the weed application is Momentum 4-Score (Triclopyr Fluroxpyp) Broadleaf Weed Control. The applicator is Nault’s Green Lawn Liquid Fertilizer, Inc.

For additional information, please contact the Director of Operations at (906) 786-4661 or acseter@eskymos.com. The National Pesticide Information Center phone number is 1-800-858-7378. The Michigan Department of Agriculture phone number is 1-800-292-3939.

post_text:
In response to the closure of school and the subsequent shift to distance learning, we distributed over 500 Chromebooks and iPads –– and over 100 Verizon Jetpacks –– for our students to use at home over the past few months. Providing these devices has helped to create a level playing field during a truly unusual spring. We’re thankful for our tech staff helping to make the distribution events run so smoothly, but also for shouldering the additional burden of off-campus device support for students and parents.

Because we’re currently unsure what school will look like in the fall, students will keep all assigned technology equipment until they hear otherwise, even if that extends into the 2020-21 school year. Once we have more information regarding next year, we’ll notify families regarding next steps. All Verizon Jetpacks assigned for student use will be disabled as of 4:00 PM on June 5th, and will either be collected at the same time as the Chromebooks/iPads or enabled again in the fall, if necessary.

A drive-thru pickup for 6th grade students to receive their locker contents and other personal belongings will be held on Friday, May 15th from 8:00 AM to 3:00 PM at EUE. Drivers should expect to remain in their vehicles and should approach the northwest doors (closest to the playground) via 16th street from the north and exit to the south, onto Ludington Street. Staff working the pickup will need the student’s name and Advisory teacher, as that’s how the belongings have been grouped.

Important: Belongings for 6th grade students with a younger sibling in 4th or 5th grade have been passed down to those teachers to reduce the number of pickups. 4th and 5th grade teachers are reaching out to their classes and will arrange specific time slots for pickups.

Please contact the EUE office by phone or email with any questions. Thanks!

post_text: Parents/Guardians: Thank you for your patience and understanding as we've transitioned to virtual learning. We are here to support you and want you to know that you can reach out to us if there is anything you need. We are required by the state to track the participation of our students with online instruction. At least once a week, we are expected to communicate with all families or show proof of student participation either by text, e-mail, phone call, Class Dojo/Remind messaging, student log in on Lexia, student submission of responses to stories or journaling, etc. If we haven't received communication with you or haven't seen participation by your student, we will be reaching out to you at the end of each week to check in and see if there is anything we can do to support you. Thanks!

Escanaba Schools would like to congratulate our very own Laura Robinson on being selected as the MSBOA District 14 Teacher of the Year!

Each year the Michigan School Band & Orchestra Association(MSBOA) Districts select a Band and Orchestra teacher they feel has shown excellence in teaching, involvement, and inspiration to their students and to the instrumental music programs across the State of Michigan. This year, MSBOA District 14 has awarded that honor to Laura Robinson, Band Director, from Escanaba Area Public Schools.

"Congrats Laura! I look forward to seeing what you continue to do and inspire both your students and all of us around you."
President Miller, District 14 MSBOA President

post_text:
EAPS is providing technology equipment in an effort to ensure students are able to take part in online instruction from home during the school closure. School staff are working to establish direct telephone contact with families to determine each household's level of access to computer and internet resources from home. The equipment will be handed out by invitation only during distribution events scheduled to take place in the near future. In order to keep this process orderly and efficient, please do not attempt to pick up equipment without first receiving a direct invitation from your school. The distribution events will involve only equipment that’s been pre-assigned to particular students, and there is no provision for ‘walk-in’ or unscheduled device pickups. Questions or comments should be directed to the appropriate school principal.

Escanaba Student Success Center students will receive devices in a similar process, but separately from the rest of the District.

shared_text:
Rhonda Sanville is at Escanaba Area Public Schools.
March 19 at 2:35 PM · Escanaba, MI ·

Hello families of 1st-6th grade students! Another option for getting some of that "homeschooling" in can be reading books online and taking Accelerated Reader tests. The testing is now open so kids can take AR tests any day of the week from 7:00 AM until 11:00 PM. Two sites that have free books for kids to read online are openlibrary.org and getepic.com. (Getepic offers a free 30 day trial.) If your child needs their log in information, I can help with that. PM me and I'll get that information to you asap. Please know we miss your kiddos and can't wait for that old M-F routine to return. Be safe and stay healthy!

shared_text:
Esky Fan Club is feeling thankful.
March 19 at 10:40 AM ·

During this time, the Fan Club would like to reach out and let everyone know we are thinking about all of our members and athlete's. Even though sports programs, schools and events have been cancelled and put on hold, we know this too shall pass. It's extremely difficult for seniors not knowing how this is all going to pan out, but know you are all in our thoughts and prayers. Our athletic program, along with the Fan Club depends so much on the generosity of our community that we ask that you make sure and support all our great businesses that donate to our programs! If you can't get to a business, please call and buy a gift certificate. Every little bit is going to help if we all pull together. Order that meal to go, fill up your gas tanks, get your car washed, shop in our hometown grocery stores, and most importantly, take care of your neighbors! Together, we will all be stronger as a result of this. Because as we all know.... ONCE AN ESKYMO, ALWAYS AN ESKYMO!! 🧡🖤🧡🖤 Stay safe everyone...

shared_text:
Escanaba Area Public Schools added 4 new photos.
March 5 at 9:29 PM ·

Unified Sports is dedicated to promoting social inclusion through athletic teamwork. In this case, our first ever Unified Eskymo Basketball team!

Unified Sports joins people with and without intellectual disabilities on the same team. It was inspired by a simple principle: training together and playing together is a quick path to friendship and understanding.

These student athletes and coaches have spent countless hours training twice a week since mid-November. Special Olympics granted the team $1,200 for jerseys and shorts, and today our juniors and seniors showcased their talents from 1:30-2:25 in the EHS gymnasium.

According to student athlete, Angel, "We aren't good enough to make the regular high school team, but we want to show everyone that we can still play and have skills." GO MOS!

Team photo, back row, left to right: Coach Ethan, Brett, Aaron, Jacob, Layne, Alan, Tavi, Rylee, Angel, Coach Peyton, Brandon, Coach Josh
front row, left to right: Paige, Ella, Zander, Hunter, Roz, Danny, Kaylee
missing: Coach Grace
